The río Magdalena system supports ca. 80 % of the total Colombian population ( 32 million people). This extreme anthropic impact has caused deforestation, an increase in erosion and sediment transport, floodplain draining, and fisheries collapse, that together severely degrade the environmental quality of habitats available for fish communities (
Galvis & Mojica, 2007
). Contrary to the long-held opinion about the completeness of our knowledge on the río Magdalena fishes, urgent efforts are required on at least two fronts: ( 1 ) biodiversity inventories in fragile systems such as piedmont tributaries, and ( 2 ) more efficient conservation policies. Without such measures, the rate of habitat degradation will continue to rise while the rate of knowledge acquisition will decrease, and the río Magdalena biodiversity will be lost even before being adequately documented.
